{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17520619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17520619"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:26:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:26:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13237"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13237","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13237"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.15,0.15,0.6,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5679"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47267"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5679","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5679"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13237"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31978"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"471"},{"type":"tags","id":"483"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5066"},{"type":"tags","id":"5069"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9864"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10555"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42857"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47267","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47267"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a one day history of left-sided chest pain associated with shortness of breath, particularly when he is lying flat. He has also noted some swelling around his ankles. His medical history include chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) and heart failure with reduced ejection. His medications include aspirin, ticagrelor, digoxin, low-dose lisinopril and ipratropium inhaler.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his blood pressure is 125/70 mmHg, pulse 114/min and regular, temperature is 37.0\u00b0C, respiratory rate 26/min and SpO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E 84% on room air. Chest auscultation finds bilateral lung crackles on lung bases and occasional wheeze.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe is given oxygen by face mask, intravenous high-dose furosemide and subcutaneous enoxaparin for DVT prophylaxis. He is advised to continue his usual dose of lisinopril and ipratropium inhaler. His dyspnoea improves over the next 24 hours and the pedal swelling resolves. However, on the 2nd post-admission day, he complained of nausea, vomiting, photopsia and visual halos. An ECG is consistent with digoxin toxicity. (Image)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely medication to have precipitated this?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aspirin","Ipratropium","Lisinopril","Furosemide","Enoxaparin"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient taking digoxin, now presenting with nausea, vomiting, visual halos and classical ECG findings of \u003Cstrong\u003EDown-sloping / \u0027scooped\u0027 ST depression\u003C/strong\u003E, aka \u0027reverse tick\u0027 or \u0027Dali moustache\u0027,\u00a0sinus bradycardia and prolonged PR-interval, is most likely having \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute digoxin toxicity \u003C/strong\u003Esecondary to furosemide use in acute decompensated heart failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFurosemide\u003C/strong\u003E and other loop diuretics induce hypokalaemia. (Image) Digoxin toxicity is typically increased in \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypokalaemic \u003C/strong\u003Esituations because digoxin typically binds to the ATPase pump at the same location as potassium. Digoxin can bind to the ATPase pump more readily and exert its inhibitory effects when potassium levels are low.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMoreover, furosemide decreases the renal clearance of digoxin, further potentiating the toxicity of digoxin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin \u003C/strong\u003Eis not known to induce digoxin toxicity. It can be given safely in patients taking digoxin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIpratropium \u003C/strong\u003Eis an antimuscarinic agent used via inhalation to dilate the respiratory tree. It has not been linked to digoxin toxicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELisinopril \u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cstrong\u003Eenoxaparin \u003C/strong\u003Eneither interact with digoxin nor cause hypokalaemia. So they can be given safely in patients taking digoxin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Digoxin toxicity presents with vomiting, photopsia and other visual disturbances.","Scooped ST depression, giving the appearance of a \u0022reverse tick\u0022, is the classic ECG finding in digoxin toxicity.","Hypokalaemia can potentiate the effect of digoxin and is the commonest cause of its toxicity."],"references":["Rehman R, Hai O. Digitalis Toxicity. [Updated 2023 May 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459165/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31978"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13237"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20579"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20402"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20579","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20579"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/u53fNkW0OGGcONtuKjB98XcFzOcqD8.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/u53fNkW0OGGcONtuKjB98XcFzOcqD8.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":751,"height":341}},{"type":"media","id":"20402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20402"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1xXXwZatAD9WJo5wS69l9m0yxWn2aX.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1xXXwZatAD9WJo5wS69l9m0yxWn2aX.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":796,"height":397}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31978","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/31978"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-19T12:08:07+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-06-19T12:08:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5679"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47267"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"t